\subsection{Plate 31: Church Accommodations by State}



\autoref{fig:plate31} shows a miniature of plate \#31 from the 1870 Statistical Atlas. This plate shows the percentage of religious sittings by denomination for each state (colored stripes in the square) as well as the percentage of unaccommodated population over the age of ten (area of the grey outer frame). For each state a square of the same size is drawn. The four most common denominations within each state are shown as colored stripes, the width of each is proportional to the number of people accommodated. Each denomination is shown by one of eleven different colors, all other denominations are represented jointly by a twelfth color. The color scheme chosen in the Statistical Atlas is essentially that of paired colors, i.e.\ each hue is represented with a lighter shade (using hatching) and a darker shade (see zoom-in to the legend of plate \#31 in Figure \ref{fig:legend-31}).

The inside squares of plate~\#31 are simpler in structure than those of plate \#32 -- they are one-dimensional mosaic plots, also known as rotated stacked bar charts or spine plots \citep{hummel:1996}. As in the previous example, a grey frame is drawn with an area proportional to the size of the unaccommodated population over the age of ten. Additionally, other design choices were made which impact the readability of the charts:

\begin{compactitem}
\item[\bf Top four only:] A decision was made to only show the top four denominations in each state and the top eight denominations in the United States. As a result, some denominations are shown which have lower overall accommodation, while other denominations are excluded even though they accommodate more people. For example,  in 1870 the Reformed Late Germans accommodated 431,700 people nation-wide; the 10th highest number, as shown in Figure \ref{fig:barchart-31}. However, they are not mentioned in plate \#32. The Mormon Church is locally (Utah Territory) strong enough to be represented, even though it accommodates only 87,838 people (17th place nationally) and is far behind the German Reformed Church. This decision was likely due in part to technical constraints: it would be very hard to align very thin bars with even high-precision lithography, as each color layer of each chart must be drawn by hand and carefully aligned. Limiting the choices to five total internal bars ensured that it was generally possible to render the image and match the colors to the denominations listed in the legend.

\item[\bf Re-ordering:] Within each state denominations are ordered from largest to smallest. This makes comparisons of the state-wide religious makeup between states more difficult, as it re-orders the colors in the bar code-like color strips representing each state, thus small differences in numbers might result in rather large visual differences.
\end{compactitem}

