@

Our participants were drawn from two different populations -- reddit and amazon mechanical turk. On reddit, participants were recruited from \href{http://reddit.com/r/samplesize}{/r/samplesize} and \href{http://reddit.com/r/visualization}{/r/visualization}; both communities are interested in data or data visualization, and thus are more likely to be data-literate than the general population. This may explain why responses from redditors have lower variability than responses from amazon mechanical turkers (see Figure\autoref{fig:participantvar}). Figure\autoref{fig:participantpref} shows responses from redditors and mechanical turkers. On the left side of the figure we see that both groups tend to round their area estimates to the nearest 5\%, as seen in the modes of the histograms. We expected that redditors might be more accurate due to greater interest in the topic; however, other than the lower variability of responses, we did not detect any significant difference between the two populations. This may indicate that the biases responsible for estimation errors are perceptual in nature and may not decrease with education or exposure. 

\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conc}
The United States Census Bureau did an incredible job at collecting, tabulating, visualizing, and maintaining the data presented in the Statistical Atlas. Reproducibility has become a highly discussed topic in science lately, but few researchers even try to preserve their data and methods in such a way that the results could be precisely duplicated 150 years later. The Census Bureau (in conjunction with the Library of Congress) has managed to make it fairly easy for researchers to access the data necessary to conduct this study online.

In addition to the technical feat of reproducibility, the Statistical Atlas, spearheaded by the vision of Francis Walker, represented a state-sponsored foray into the development and use of new types of charts. With 107 pages of charts, and several relatively new types of plots, it is not surprising that some of these experiments fell flat. While framed plots are aesthetically appealing, they are not effective at communicating numerical information accurately. In addition, there are several design choices made in plates 31 and 32 which can be attributed to the technological limitations of hand-drawn plots. These design choices are not ideal from a modern perspective, but are perfectly reasonable when viewed in light of the technological constraints of lithography. While we have established that using framed plots is a suboptimal design choice, we acknowledge that the plots have a certain visual appeal. It is possible that the creators of the Statistical Atlas recognized the failed experiment, as framed plots do not appear in the 1880 or 1890 atlases.

Of the successes which underlie the creation of the 1870 Statistical Atlas, it would be better to leave the framed charts in the annals of history and focus on the remarkably resilient infrastructure which allows us to test the effectiveness of these plots 150 years later.


